<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm">
  <title>Bounded Harmonic Functions and Differentiable Functions of a Complex Variable</title>
<page>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this worksheet, you will prove one major additional property of harmonic functions. 
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise><title>Bounded Harmonic Functions are Constant</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
        Suppose <m>u</m> is harmonic on <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and <m>|u|&lt; M</m> for some <m>M&gt; 0</m>. Prove that <m>u</m> is a constant function as follows:
    </p>

</introduction>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> be points in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. Explain why
            <md>
                u(x_1) - u(x_2) = \frac{1}{\pi R^2}\int\int_{B_R(x_1)} u(r,\theta) dA - \frac{1}{\pi R^2}\int\int_{B_R(x_2)} u(r,\theta) dA
            </md>
            where <m>R</m> is the same for both integrals.
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>d = \|x_1 - x_2\|</m>. Combine the integrals from the last part into a single integral and sketch its region of integration. Give a geometric/algebraic argument that the area of this region is less than <m>\pi d(2R + d)</m>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Give an upper bound for <m>|u(x_1) - u(x_2)|</m> based on previous parts and show that this approaches zero as <m>R\to\infty</m>. Say why this proves <m>u</m> is constant.
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>

  
    
  </exercise>

  <p>
    Consider a function <m>f:\mathbb{C}\to\mathbb{C}</m>. Observe that letting <m>z = x+iy</m>, we can write 
    <md>
        f(z) = u(x,y) + iv(x,y).
    </md>
    We say <m>f</m> is differentiable if 
    <md>
        <mrow> f'(z) = \amp \lim_{\Delta z \to 0}\frac{f(z+\Delta z) - f(z)}{\Delta z} </mrow>
        <mrow>  = \amp \lim_{\Delta x, \Delta y\to 0}\frac{u(x + \Delta x , y + \Delta y) - u(x,y)}{\sqrt{\Delta x^2 + \Delta y^2}} + i \frac{v(x + \Delta x , y + \Delta y) - v(x,y)}{\sqrt{\Delta x^2 + \Delta y^2}}</mrow>
    </md>
    exists.
    
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
    <p>
        Suppose a function <m>f:\mathbb{C}\to\mathbb{C}</m> is differentiable. By taking limits with <m>\Delta x = 0</m> and <m>\Delta y = 0</m> separately, show that 
    <md>
       u_x = v_y \text{ and } u_y = -v_x. 
    </md>
    </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
                With <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> as above, show that <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are harmonic. Thus, conclude that bounded differentiable functions of a complex variable are constant (what does boundedness mean here?). 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</page>

</worksheet>
